<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE HISTORY TEACHER, BY BILLY COLLINS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Trying to protect his student's innocence 
</P>
<P>
 he told them the Ice Age was really just 
</P>
<P>
 the Chilly Age, a period of a million years 
</P>
<P>
 when everyone had to wear sweaters. 
</P>
<P>
 And the Stone Age became the Gravel Age, 
</P>
<P>
 named after the long driveways of the time. 
</P>
<P>
 The Spanish Inquisition was nothing more 
</P>
<P>
 than an outbreak of questions such as 
</P>
<P>
 "How far is it from here to Madrid?" 
</P>
<P>
 "What do you call the matador's hat?" 
</P>
<P>
 The War of the Roses took place in a garden, 
</P>
<P>
 and the Enola Gay dropped one tiny atom 
</P>
<P>
 on Japan. 
</P>
<P>
 The children would leave his classroom 
</P>
<P>
 for the playground and torment the weak 
</P>
<P>
 and the smart, 
</P>
<P>
 mussing up their hair and breaking their glasses, 
</P>
<P>
 while he gathered his notes and walked home 
</P>
<P>
 past flower beds and white picket fences, 
</P>
<P>
 wondering if they would believe that soldiers 
</P>
<P>
 in the Boer War told long, rambling stories 
</P>
<P>
 designed to make the enemy nod off. 
</P>
<P>
 From "Stand Up Poetry: The Anthology" edited by Charles H. Webb. (The 
University Press, California State University, Long Beach: $9.95) 1994 
Reprinted by permission.  
</P>
