<TEXT>
<P>
 AMERICAN NATURE WRITING 1994 edited by John A. Murray (Sierra Club Books: $12; 
229 pp., paperback original). This volume marks the debut of an annual 
collection of essays "by new and distinguished voices."The most resonant 
entries are from familiar authors: Rick Bass calls for a ban on logging in the 
Yaak Valley of Montana with his familiar, eloquent passion; Barry Lopez deftly 
juxtaposes memories of apartment life in Manhattan and camping trips near the 
Grand Canyon. Among the new contributors, Sherry Simpson vividly describes the 
fear she felt watching a biologist tag anesthetized bears in Alaska. On the 
down side, Russell Chatham's account of salmon fishing in Iceland conflicts 
with spirit of the anthology, while Jennifer Brice's attempt to mythologize her 
pregnancy seems pretentious and artsy. 
