<HEADLINE>
<P>
PAPERBACKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 MAMA MAKES UP HER MIND AND OTHER DANGERS OF SOUTHERN LIVING by Bailey White 
(Vintage: $10.; 229 pp.). The popular National Public Radio commentator 
discusses life in rural Georgia in these lively vignettes.Her eccentric, often 
cantankerous mother, who cooks road-kill animals and assumes command of any 
social situation, dominates the book. White describes her mother's house as a 
sort of beach where the flotsam of several generations has come to rest. When 
she attempts to clean for a visit from prospective in-laws, "Mama would not let 
us throw out a box of old photographs we found under the sofa -- 'I may 
remember who those people are someday.' " Readers who listen to "All Things 
Considered" will hear White's familiar drawl as they savor these memoirs of an 
unusual yet ordinary life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
