</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 THE SAINT: Alias the Saint by Leslie Charters (Carroll & Graf: $3.95; 179 pp.) 
. Long out of print, these two adventures introduce a new generation of readers 
to one of the great detectives of the '30s. Elegant, suave and irreverent, 
Simon Templer resembles Philo Vance more than Sam Spade: In "The National 
Debt," he appears "arrayed in green pajamas and a staggering silk dressing gown 
that would have made Joseph's coat look like a suit of deep mourning." 
Charters' polished descriptions will engage readers who only know his famous 
character from the old Roger Moore TV series. 
</P>
</TEXT>
