<HEADLINE>
<P>
MARGARET LEE PERENCHIO; STUDIO SECRETARY TURNED SCREENWRITER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Margaret Lee Perenchio, 89, studio secretary who became a screenwriter and 
author. Born in Calumet, Mich., Miss Perenchio moved to Fresno with her family 
when she was a teen-ager.She began her career in Hollywood in the office at 
Paramount and later worked as Harry Cohn's executive assistant at Columbia. 
Encouraged by Cohn, she began writing, and co-wrote the screenplay for actress 
Marion Davies' final film, "Ever Since Eve" in 1937. Miss Perenchio co-authored 
the book "If This Be My Harvest" in 1948, and a year later she wrote the 
screenplay "The Bright Dame" for a film starring James Cagney. She also wrote 
episodes for CBS' "You Are There." Her hobby was competitive ballroom dancing. 
On June 3 in Los Angeles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
