<HEADLINE>
<P>
'NONPARTISAN' A MISNOMER FOR RACE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * Reading the newspapers last Thursday morning ("Silva Picks Up Tillotson's 
Endorsement," June 9) should make Democrats supporting Linda Moulton Patterson 
in her "nonpartisan" race for (Orange County) supervisor face reality. Get mad 
and get even! 
</P>
<P>
 "There is no such thing as a nonpartisan race in Orange County," said 
Supervisor William G. Steiner. County Supervisor Roger Stanton warned local 
business people that Moulton Patterson, by virtue of her Democratic Party 
affiliation, represented a serious threat to the board's conservative style of 
governing. 
</P>
<P>
 When Jim Silva, the other candidate for county supervisor in our District 2, 
obviously welcomes Republican help, must Moulton Patterson shun evidence of 
political affiliation? 
</P>
<P>
 I say "No." She should welcome the support of the 89,456 Democrats in District 
2, go after the 941 Greens, the 1,988 Libertarians, the 4,514 American 
Independents, the 859 Peace and Freedom voters, the 310 miscellaneous and of 
course the 26,773 nonpartisan or "decline to state" voters -- and yes, 
Republicans. Within those 249,953 Republican voters, there must be a lot who 
care more about issues than party affiliation. Republicans should recognize 
that the county, as an administrative unit of the state, will benefit by having 
at least one supervisor with Democratic credibility to make Orange County's 
case with the state Legislature. 
</P>
<P>
 The county loses at least $45 million each year because the state's allocation 
policy on health and welfare services was formulated years ago, when Orange 
County Republican leadership refused state and federal funds. Too late, the 
Republican leadership recognized there was unemployment, homelessness and 
poverty in wealthy Orange County. 
</P>
<P>
 Now, with the state's fiscal crunch, the Republican supervisors have not been 
able to change the formula. Orange County continues not to receive appropriate 
allocation of funds as do other counties. 
</P>
<P>
 SALLY J. ALEXANDER 
</P>
<P>
 Huntington Beach 
</P>
<P>
 Sally J. Alexander is Candidate Support Chair for the Democratic Club of West 
Orange County and a former regional director for the California Democratic 
Party.  
</P>
