<P>
YOUTH COULD BE 1ST UNDER NEW RULING TO FACE MURDER CHARGES IN DEATH OF FETUS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In what may be the first case of its kind in California, a Fresno teen-ager 
could be charged with murder in connection with the shooting death of his 
girlfriend's fetus. 
</P>
<P>
 The 4-month fetus died Friday, a day after Ramon Orosco, 18, shot his 
14-year-old pregnant girlfriend in the back for talking with another boy, 
police said.Maria Torres was listed in extremely critical condition at Fresno's 
Valley Medical Center. 
</P>
<P>
 Assistant Dist. Atty. Robert Freed said Orosco will be charged with murder. 
Because of a state Supreme Court ruling in May, the killing of a non-viable 
fetus can be considered murder. Previously, the court held that a murder charge 
was warranted only if the fetus was old enough to survive at birth. 
