<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP '94; WORLD CUP USA '94 GROUP A PREVIEW; AMERICA'S TEAM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Team USA is a true melting pot. Seven of the 22 members of the U.S. national 
soccer team were born outside the country, two in Uruguay. 
</P>
<P>
 Two of the imports were the sons of U.S. military personnel stationed abroad; 
three moved to the United States with their families as children. One attended 
college here, the other established himself as one of the best players in Major 
Indoor Soccer League history. 
</P>
<P>
 The other 15 team members have varied backgrounds. They hail from nine states, 
including four from California and three from New Jersey. Perhaps the most 
important import of all is Coach Bora Milutinovic, who directed Mexico and 
Costa Rica in previous World Cups, and was born in Bajina Basta, Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
 Seven U.S. team members -- John Harkes (Derby County, England), Cle Kooiman 
(Cruz Azul, Mexico), Tab Ramos (Real Betis, Spain), Juergen Sommer (Luton Town, 
England), Ernie Stewart (Willem II, Netherlands), Roy Wegerle (Coventry City, 
England) and Eric Wynalda (FC Saarbrucken, Germany) -- play in European pro 
leagues. THE COACH 
</P>
<P>
 NAME: Bora Milutinovic 
</P>
<P>
 BORN: Sept. 7, 1944, Bajina Basta, Yugoslavia 
</P>
<P>
 CUP EXPERIENCE: Led Mexico to a sixth-place finish in 1986 and Costa Rica to 
the second round in 1990. His teams are 5-2-2. 
</P>
<P>
 HIGHLIGHTS: Has coached in more than 150 international matches, believed to be 
a record ... Played 33 matches with the Yugoslavian national team ... Spent 12 
years as a player and coach with the Universidad Autonoma de Mexico Pumas. He 
coached the team to two Mexican first division titles, two CONCACAF club 
championships and an inter-Americana Cup title ... Mexico's 1986 World Cup team 
played West Germany to a scoreless tie before losing on penalty kicks ... 
Directed the U.S. team to a CONCACAF Gold Cup title in 1991 and a 2-0 upset of 
England in U.S. Cup '93. THE ASSISTANTS 
</P>
<P>
 Timo Liekoski 
</P>
<P>
 Sigi Schmid 
</P>
<P>
 Steve Sampson 
</P>
<P>
 Milutin Soskic THE PLAYERS 
</P>
