<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP '94; WORLD CUP USA '94 / GROUP B PREVIEW; CAMEROON AT A GLANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Grahame L. Jones 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * COACH: Henri Michel. 
</P>
<P>
 * KEY PLAYERS: Francois Omam-Biyick, Alphonse Tchami, Stephen Tataw. 
</P>
<P>
 * STRENGTHS: The sheer exuberance and unpredictability of Cameroon's play 
makes the team a pleasure to watch. The players have a gift for trying the 
unusual and the unexpected. They get speed, skill and firepower from 
Omam-Biyick and Tchami and solid defensive leadership from Tataw. 
</P>
<P>
 * WEAKNESSES: A chaotic situation at home, where the federation is bankrupt 
and politicians have meddled constantly in team affairs, has left Cameroon 
ill-prepared for this tournament. Of course, the same thing was true in 1990 
and look what happened. Roger Milla, Cameroon's hero of Italia '90, is back, 
but he's 42 and shows it. 
</P>
<P>
 * WORLD CUP HISTORY: Two previous appearances. Record of 3-2-3. Went unbeaten 
in the first round in 1982 but still failed to advance. Best finish was 
reaching the quarterfinals in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
 * LITTLE-KNOWN FACT: Veterans Milla and goalkeeper Thomas N'Kono have each 
twice been chosen Africa's player of the year -- Milla in 1976 and 1990 and 
N'Kono in 1979 and 1982. 
</P>
<P>
 * OUTLOOK: Logic says this is the year Cameroon fails to get out of the first 
round, but the Africans have a habit of confounding the experts and could do so 
again. Their first-round opposition, however, is formidable. The 
Brazil-Cameroon match could be a classic. Sweden should be physically and 
tactically too strong. The Soviet Union trounced Cameroon, 4-0, in Italy last 
time around. 
</P>
<P>
