<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP '94; WORLD CUP USA '94 / GROUP B PREVIEW; BRAZIL AT A GLANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Grahame L. Jones 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * COACH: Carlos Alberto Parreira. 
</P>
<P>
 * KEY PLAYERS: Romario, Bebeto, Rai. 
</P>
<P>
 * STRENGTHS: The finest all-around team in the tournament, with strength in 
depth at almost every position. Strikers Romario and Bebeto are among the best 
in the world. Right back Jorginho and his understudy, Cafu, are defenders whose 
overlapping runs down the wing create numerous chances. The team has abundant 
skill in all aspects of the game. 
</P>
<P>
 * WEAKNESSES: Midfield could be a problem. Playmaker Rai did not do well in 
his first season in France, possibly because he was played out of position. The 
defense is solid but can sometimes be caught because of the players' enthusiasm 
for joining the attack. Goalkeeping is no more than adequate. 
</P>
<P>
 * WORLD CUP HISTORY: Fourteen previous appearances. Record of 44-11-11. Winner 
in 1958, 1962 and 1970; runner-up 1950; third place in 1938 and 1978; fourth 
place 1974. The only country to have played in every World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
 * LITTLE-KNOWN FACT: Brazil and Germany have played a total of 134 World Cup 
matches but have never met in the competition. 
</P>
<P>
 * OUTLOOK: Brazil is the favorite to win it all and there is no reason to 
suspect that it will not, despite a 1-1 tie with Canada in Edmonton last week. 
The first round will provide no obstacle. The only teams that could possibly 
derail Brazilian hopes for a fourth title are Colombia and Germany. 
</P>
<P>
