<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP '94; WORLD CUP USA '94 / GROUP C PREVIEW; BOLIVIA AT A GLANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Grahame L. Jones 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * COACH: Xavier Azkargorta. 
</P>
<P>
 * KEY PLAYERS: Erwin Sanchez, Luis Hector Cristaldo, Julio Cesar Baldivieso. 
</P>
<P>
 * STRENGTHS: Bolivia has speed and skill aplenty, with a fondness for playing 
possession soccer and attacking down the wings. Sanchez, nicknamed "Platini" 
after former French star Michel Platini, is a playmaking midfielder of some 
note. Baldivieso is in form and has played well recently. 
</P>
<P>
 * WEAKNESSES: The loss of Marco Etcheverry, who suffered torn knee ligaments 
in November and is on the team but seems unlikely to play, will hurt. So will 
not having the advantage of playing at high altitude, as the Bolivians do in La 
Paz. They also are likely to be intimidated by physically stronger and larger 
opponents. 
</P>
<P>
 * WORLD CUP HISTORY: Two previous appearances. Record of 0-3-0. Never advanced 
beyond the first round. 
</P>
<P>
 * LITTLE-KNOWN FACT: Azkargorta, a Basque from Spain, was chosen Bolivia's man 
of the year in 1993 after the team's successful qualifying run. 
</P>
<P>
 * OUTLOOK: With little experience at this level, a relatively young team and 
strong opposition, it is difficult to envision Bolivia lasting long in the 
tournament. The key to a possible third-place finish in the first round will be 
the match against South Korea. 
</P>
