<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP '94; WORLD CUP USA '94 / GROUP C PREVIEW; GERMANY AT A GLANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Grahame L. Jones 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * COACH: Berti Vogts. 
</P>
<P>
 * KEY PLAYERS: Juergen Klinsmann, Andreas Moeller, Lothar Matthaeus. 
</P>
<P>
 * STRENGTHS: Disciplined, well-organized and exceptionally experienced, the 
Germans are again among the favorites. As defending champions, they know what 
it takes to pace themselves through the seven matches needed to win the Cup. 
Klinsmann leads the attack. Moeller, helped by Thomas Haessler, will organize 
the midfield, and Matthaeus is supposed to hold the defense intact. 
</P>
<P>
 * WEAKNESSES: If Klinsmann can be stopped, Germany has struggled to find 
another consistent goal scorer. The defense is either well-seasoned or ready to 
crumble, depending on the viewpoint. Heat could be a factor in making the older 
players feel their age. 
</P>
<P>
 * WORLD CUP HISTORY: Twelve previous appearances. Record of 39-15-14. Winner 
in 1954, 1974, 1990; runner-up in 1966, 1982 and 1986; third in 1934 and 1970; 
fourth in 1958. 
</P>
<P>
 * LITTLE-KNOWN FACT: Former German star Wolfgang Overath is the only player in 
history to have played on teams that finished first, second and third in the 
World Cup, doing so in 1974, 1966 and 1970, respectively. If Germany finishes 
third in this tournament, several other players will join him, since Germany 
has been second and first in the last two Cups. 
</P>
<P>
 * OUTLOOK: Germany has benefited from having perhaps the easiest of the 
first-round groups. It is impossible to see Bolivia, Spain or South Korea 
giving Germany any difficulties. The organization of the competition puts the 
Germans on track to meet Argentina or Italy somewhere along the way. If they 
are not upset then, they will be in the final for a record fourth consecutive 
time. 
</P>
<P>
