<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP '94; WORLD CUP USA '94 / GROUP C PREVIEW; SPAIN AT A GLANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Grahame L. Jones 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * COACH: Javier Clemente. 
</P>
<P>
 * KEY PLAYERS: Andoni Zubizarreta, Julen Guerrero, Julio Salinas. 
</P>
<P>
 * STRENGTHS: Spain's 22 players are drawn entirely from the Spanish League, 
including nine from FC Barcelona, so the players know each other well. 
Goalkeeper Zubizarreta has vast experience and is Spain's all-time leader in 
international appearances with 86. Guerrero, 20, is the team's future star, a 
midfielder of exceptional skill in both setting up plays and finishing them. 
Salinas is a striker who can't keep his place on the Barcelona team yet scores 
goals with regularity for the national team. 
</P>
<P>
 * WEAKNESSES: Difficult to pinpoint on a team noted more for its industrious 
nature than for any outstanding quality. Zubizarreta recently was fired by 
Barcelona, which might inspire him to prove the club wrong or might have 
shattered his confidence. If Clemente is too cautious and does not give the 
rising stars a chance to shine, Spain will look ordinary. 
</P>
<P>
 * WORLD CUP HISTORY: Eight previous appearances. Record of 13-12-7. Best 
finish was fourth place in 1950. 
</P>
<P>
 * LITTLE-KNOWN FACT: Spain has lost only two matches since Clemente took 
charge in 1992--to European champion Denmark and, surprisingly, to Croatia. 
</P>
<P>
 * OUTLOOK: Neither Bolivia nor South Korea should pose any major difficulty in 
the first round and Spain should reach the last 16 with ease. 
</P>
<P>
