<SECTION>
<P>
Special Section; Part W; Page 15; Column 3; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
319 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP '94; WORLD CUP USA '94 / GROUP C PREVIEW; SOUTH KOREA AT A GLANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Grahame L. Jones 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * COACH: Kim Ho. 
</P>
<P>
 * KEY PLAYERS: Hwang Sun-nong, Kim Joo-sung, Choi In-young. 
</P>
<P>
 * STRENGTHS: The offense boasts above-average speed, determination and a fair 
amount of technical skill.Midfielder Kim Joo-sung played on the 1986 and 1990 
World Cup teams and has twice been named Asia's player of the year. Seo 
Jung-won, another midfielder, is one of the fastest players in the tournament. 
</P>
<P>
 * WEAKNESSES: Youth, lack of international experience and a lack of 
self-confidence are the main difficulties the Koreans have to overcome. Their 
defense is somewhat naive and not as tenacious as it should be once beaten. The 
team's sometimes overly enthusiastic, not to say rough play could result in 
problems with referees. 
</P>
<P>
 * WORLD CUP HISTORY: Three previous appearances. Record of 0-7-1. Never 
advanced beyond the first round. 
</P>
<P>
 * LITTLE-KNOWN FACT: South Korea's technical adviser, Anatoli Byshovets, 
coached the Soviet Union's gold medal-winning side in the 1988 Seoul Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
 * OUTLOOK: South Korea will have good fan support in Dallas and is talented 
enough to score its first World Cup victory by defeating Bolivia and thereby 
possibly reaching the second round. 
</P>
<P>
 * PREDICTED FIRST-ROUND FINISH: Third. ROSTER 03,05,16,12 No. Name Position 1 
Choi In-young Goalkeeper 21 Park Chul-woo Goalkeeper 22 Lee Woon-jae Goalkeeper 
2 Chung John-son Defender 3 Lee Jong-hwa Defender 4 Kim Pan-keun Defender 5 
Park Jung-bae Defender 6 Lee Young-sang Defender 7 Shin Hong-gi Defender 12 
