<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP '94; WORLD CUP USA '94 / GROUP E PREVIEW; NORWAY AT A GLANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Grahame L. Jones 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * COACH: Egil Olsen. 
</P>
<P>
 * KEY PLAYERS: Rune Bratseth, Erik Thorstvedt, Jan Age Fjortoft. 
</P>
<P>
 * STRENGTHS: Norway makes no apologies for using a virtually impregnable 
defense to get the results it desires. It is a frustrating team to watch and to 
play against because of this negative approach. Bratseth is a top-level sweeper 
with experience in the German Bundesliga. Several of the players are with 
English clubs, which could be a plus but probably is not. Goalkeeper Thorstvedt 
is experienced and reliable. 
</P>
<P>
 * WEAKNESSES: Scoring goals is always going to be a problem for a team that 
emphasizes defense. There is a general lack of imagination about the 
Norwegians' play, but midfielder Jostein Flo and striker Fjortoft were in form 
at the end of the English season and scoring goals regularly, so perhaps there 
is hope. 
</P>
<P>
 * WORLD CUP HISTORY: One previous appearance. Record of 0-1-0. Never advanced 
beyond the first round. 
</P>
<P>
 * LITTLE-KNOWN FACT: In Norway's official media guide, Olsen, the team's 
coach, lists his marital status as follows: "Living together with Sigrun, two 
children." He also claims to have made more money from playing poker than from 
coaching. 
</P>
<P>
 * OUTLOOK: If the Norwegians can withstand the heat, their defense is enough 
to frustrate the Irish and Mexicans, and possibly even the Italians, and earn 
them a place in the second round. 
</P>
<P>
