<DATE>
<P>
June 12, 1994, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Special Section; Part W; Page 25; Column 1; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
380 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP '94; WORLD CUP USA '94 / GROUP E PREVIEW; MEXICO AT A GLANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Grahame L. Jones 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * COACH: Miguel Mejia Baron. 
</P>
<P>
 * KEY PLAYERS: Hugo Sanchez, Luis Roberto (Zaguinho) Alves, Jorge Campos. 
</P>
<P>
 * STRENGTHS: Mexico has rebounded into the international forefront over the 
past two or three years, with players such as striker Luis Garcia, defender 
Ramon Ramirez and goalkeeper Campos all catching the eye. Sanchez can still 
provide the passes that lead to goals and Zaguinho can find the net in all 
sorts of ways. Campos can be an asset or a liability, depending on the day. 
</P>
<P>
 * WEAKNESSES: Lack of confidence seems to be the Mexicans' main problem. They 
should have handled the United States with ease at the Rose Bowl, but instead 
of maintaining pressure on the Americans they let their heads drop when 
frustrated and physically challenged and wound up losing, 1-0. Campos' habit of 
trying to be a "sweeper-keeper" could cost the team dearly, just as it did 
Colombia's Rene Higuita in 1990. Injury apparently has diluted Ramirez's 
effectiveness as an overlapping left back. 
</P>
<P>
 * WORLD CUP HISTORY: Nine previous appearances. Record of 6-17-6. Best finish 
was in reaching the quarterfinals in 1970 and 1986. 
</P>
<P>
 * LITTLE-KNOWN FACT: Hugo Sanchez is the only one of all 528 players in the 
1994 tournament to have taken part in the 1978 World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
 * OUTLOOK: Unless it can raise its game back to the level of 1993, when it won 
the CONCACAF Gold Cup and finished second in the Copa America, Mexico will be 
lucky to squeak into the second round as a third-place team. 
</P>
<P>
