<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP '94; WORLD CUP USA '94 / GROUP F PREVIEW; NETHERLANDS AT A GLANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Grahame L. Jones 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * COACH: Dick Advocaat. 
</P>
<P>
 * KEY PLAYERS: Frank Rijkaard, Dennis Bergkamp, Ronald Koeman. 
</P>
<P>
 * STRENGTHS: Bergkamp is developing into one of the world's best strikers, 
even though he had a relatively poor first season in Italy. Rijkaard, the only 
member of AC Milan's former world-beating Dutch trio to make the trip (Ruud 
Gullit left the team, Marco Van Basten is recovering from injury) provides the 
know-how in midfield, and Koeman is a free-kick specialist. The Dutch also 
attack well down either wing. 
</P>
<P>
 * WEAKNESSES: There is turmoil in the camp, as usual. Gullit walking out on 
the team was a blow, as was Van Basten first saying yes, then no, to joining 
the squad. Koeman is 31 and his lack of mobility and pace has been exposed on 
occasion recently. He is also prone to professional fouls when beaten, 
something that definitely will result in a red card in '94. The goalkeeping has 
yet to be tested. 
</P>
<P>
 * WORLD CUP HISTORY: Five previous appearances. Record of 8-6-6. Best finish 
was as runner-up in 1974 and 1978. 
</P>
<P>
 * LITTLE-KNOWN FACT: In 1967, as a 19-year-old, Advocaat played for San 
Francisco in the United Soccer Assn., one of the forerunners of the North 
American Soccer League. He later played for three seasons with the NASL's 
Chicago Sting. 
</P>
<P>
 * OUTLOOK: The first round should be a breeze, even if the Dutch suffer in the 
heat and humidity. Thereafter, it gets tougher. A semifinal place is not beyond 
the realm of possibility, but Colombia and Brazil loom large on the 
Netherlands' horizon. 
</P>
<P>
