<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP '94; WORLD CUP USA '94 / GROUP F PREVIEW; SAUDI ARABIA AT A GLANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Grahame L. Jones 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * COACH: Jorge Solari. 
</P>
<P>
 * KEY PLAYERS: Majed Mohammed, Khaled Al Muwallid, Sami Al Jaber. 
</P>
<P>
 * STRENGTHS: Saudi Arabia is one of the rising soccer powers in its part of 
the world. The government, that is to say, the royal family, has spent millions 
of dollars on the sport over the past 18 years or so and has been rewarded 
first with an Olympic Games appearance in 1984, an under-17 world championship 
in 1989 and now a World Cup appearance. 
</P>
<P>
 * WEAKNESSES: The Saudis change coaches at the drop of a burnoose, sending 
them packing whenever things go wrong. As a result, the players always are 
changing training methods and tactics. Small wonder they have had little 
success outside Asia and the Arab world. 
</P>
<P>
 * WORLD CUP HISTORY: First appearance. 
</P>
<P>
 * LITTLE-KNOWN FACT: In gratitude for having qualified for the World Cup for 
the first time in the nation's history, the Saudi government reportedly gave 
each player a luxury car and $100,000. 
</P>
<P>
 * OUTLOOK: The team is one of the youngest, if not the youngest, in the 
tournament. It will struggle against such experienced powers as the Netherlands 
and Belgium but will put up a fight against Morocco in the hope that a victory 
might put it in the second round. 
</P>
<P>
